<br>
AFP[ FRIDAY, JANUARY 03, 2003 01:35:26 PM ]<br>
 <br>
BEIJING: China on Friday said other countries had no right to interfere in its arms trade with Israel, following a report that the Jewish state had halted contacts on weapons sales to China at the request of the United States.<br>
<br>
&quot;It is China's consistent position that the development of normal military trade cooperation with Israel is a matter between the two countries,&quot; the foreign ministry said in a statement. &quot;Other countries have no right to interfere in this.&quot;<br>
<br>
Israel's Haaretz daily reported on Thursday that Israel had frozen all its contacts on arms and security equipment exports to China at Washington's request.<br>
<br>
The United States justified its demand with fears that advanced US defence technology contained in Israeli equipment could be used against China's arch foe Taiwan, the paper said. But an Israeli official quoted by the newspaper argued the United States could also be maneuvering to save the lucrative Chinese market for its own industry and overtake Israel in the exports race.<br>
<br>
On Thursday evening the US State Department admitted it opposed Israeli sales of high-tech weapons systems to China but insisted the position was based solely on &quot;strategic concerns&quot; and not its commercial interests.<br>
